":"1265","1319":"1319","Saltoun, West Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"East Saltoun, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Cupar, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Cupar, Fife, Scotland","Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Haddington, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Saltoun, West Haddingtonshire, East Lothianb, Scotland":"East Saltoun, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","East Saltoun, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"East Saltoun, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Abernethy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Abernathy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abernathy","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Abernethy in southeastern Perthshire. The placename is of Pictish origin, meaning ‘mouth of the river Nethy’.","History: This was the name of a cadet branch of MacDuff earls of Fife and one of the surnames of the Scots who settled in northern Ireland during the ‘plantation’ in the 17th century, and it was brought to the US as the name of a Southern plantation owner (in a different sense of the word ‘plantation’)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Abernethy 2nd of Saltoun was born in 1252, in East Saltoun, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, 